node.text:
After a childhood accident left her with disfiguring burns, YouTube beauty star @shalomblac endured bullying and low self-esteem. "I believed what people were calling me—monster, two-faced, scar-face. I didn't see beauty in myself," Blac says.
.
Now, Blac has no regrets about being candid about her experience—or her decision to face the world without makeup for the first time. "The day I decided to take a chance and challenge myself was the day I felt like I really started my journey," she explains. "That moment, I felt so relieved. I felt like a weight was taken off my shoulders."
.
FULL INTERVIEW: https://bit.ly/3m7mkJP

node.title: Burn Survivor Shalom Blac on finding the courage to share her scars

node.text:
Iskra Lawrence wants people to know that anyone can struggle with an eating disorder: "We think of 'eating disorder' and immediately go to a white anorexic woman," Lawrence says. "But that's not the case. Eating disorders have many different forms." 
.
FULL STORY: https://bit.ly/3xCNVo9

node.title: #IskraLawrence breaks down her journey towards loving her body

.

node.text:
After experiencing severe bloating, Dafina Malovska went to see her doctor who brushed it off and told her it was food-related. "My stomach was so swollen I couldn't even see my feet when I looked down," she said. Knowing something wasn't right, she decided to get a second opinion. That's when they discovered it—a 5.5-inch tumor on her uterus. 
.
FULL STORY: https://rb.gy/evfm4g

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 23, 2021. May be an image of ‎text that says '‎The FDA Has Given Full Approval to the Pfizer COVID-19 Vaccine رساون 야이‎'‎.

node.text:
The US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) has approved the Pfizer-BioNTech COVID-19 vaccine for ages 16 and older. It is the first COVID-19 vaccine in the US to receive the approval. The vaccine continues to be available under emergency use authorization for those ages 12-15 as well as for the administration of a third dose in certain immunocompromised individuals.
.
“The FDA’s approval of this vaccine is a milestone as we continue to battle the COVID-19 pandemic. While this and other vaccines have met the FDA’s rigorous, scientific standards for emergency use authorization, as the first FDA-approved COVID-19 vaccine, the public can be very confident that this vaccine meets the high standards for safety, effectiveness, and manufacturing quality the FDA requires of an approved product,” Acting FDA Commissioner Janet Woodcock, MD, said in a press release. “While millions of people have already safely received COVID-19 vaccines, we recognize that for some, the FDA approval of a vaccine may now instill additional confidence to get vaccinated. Today’s milestone puts us one step closer to altering the course of this pandemic in the US.” 
.
The fact that the Pfizer vaccine now has full FDA approval means it has undergone the agency’s standard process for reviewing the quality, safety, and effectiveness of medical products. That includes a review of: preclinical and clinical data and information, details of the manufacturing process, vaccine testing results to ensure vaccine quality, and inspections of the sites where the vaccine is made. The FDA also did its own analyses to make sure the vaccine is safe and effective. 
.
“We have not lost sight that the COVID-19 public health crisis continues in the US and that the public is counting on safe and effective vaccines. The public and medical community can be confident that although we approved this vaccine expeditiously, it was fully in keeping with our existing high standards for vaccines in the US,” Peter Marks, MD, PhD, director of FDA’s Center for Biologics Evaluation and Research, said in a press release.
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story with more info 👆

node.text:
@queendandridge is sharing her observations on how Covid has affected NICU nurses like herself:
.
"1.) Some pregnant moms are dying from Covid leaving behind motherless children. Being a nurse caring for a baby and knowing it will never see it’s mother is one of the hardest things I’ve had to do.

2.) Parents that have COVID can’t visit their sick baby for 14 days. Once they can visit only one parent can visit, to limit the amount of people in the hospital.

3.) Babies that do test positive for COVID are on isolation precaution. Most likely, if they are born really early they are on ventilators and they might be for a long time.

4.) NICU nurses are getting pulled to work in the ER or different adult units. Listen the last thing you want is a NICU nurse in the ER. Trust me.

5.) The hospitals are at capacity. Seriously, there are no beds left. Houston is the 4th largest city in the country and we are maxed out. This is not make believe."
.
She summed it up, "I’m just speaking to anyone who reads this….Wear a mask sis. It literally can cost you your life or the life of someone you love. Signed a nurse who has witnessed death and prays you never have to. ✨"

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 21, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Dead Butt Syndrome Is One More Reason You Shouldn't Sit All Day'.

node.text:
It's no secret that sitting for long stretches isn't great for your body. Research has linked it to heart disease, obesity, diabetes, even cancer. But there's another health risk from sitting all day that you might not know about: gluteal amnesia, or dead butt syndrome.
.
It almost sounds like a joke, but it's not uncommon, says Andrew Bang, a chiropractor at the Cleveland Clinic's Wellness Institute: "I see the injury all the time in varying degrees."
.
Dead butt syndrome develops when the gluteus medius—one of the three main muscles in the booty—stops firing correctly. That can happen if you spend too much time parked in a chair, explains Kristen Schuyten, a physical therapist at Michigan Medicine. "But it can also occur in very active individuals who just don't engage the glute muscles enough.”
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story, including how you can avoid dead butt syndrome 👆

node.text:
#MelissaJoanHart revealed she has a breakthrough case of COVID-19 in an emotional new video: "I am vaccinated, and I got COVID," she said. "And it's bad. It's weighing on my chest, it's hard to breathe."
.
"I'm mad," she continued, holding back tears. "I'm really mad because we tried, and we took precautions, and we cut our exposure by a lot, but we got a little lazy. And I think as a country we got lazy, and I'm really mad that my kids didn't have to wear masks at school because I'm pretty sure that's where this came from."
.
To end her video, Hart left viewers with this message: "I'm just scared and sad and disappointed in myself and some of our leaders and a lot of people, including myself, and I just wish I had done better. So I'm asking you guys to do better. Protect your families, protect your kids. It's not over yet. I hoped it was, but it's not. So stay vigilant and stay safe."
.

node.text: Turns out, Joey Tribbiani and Chandler Bing might not be the best sources of medical advice. In an episode of “Friends,” the two men helped popularize the myth that peeing on a jellyfish sting can make it feel better. But we reached out to experts, and they had different advice. Tap the link in our bio for the full story 👆

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Health on August 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Does Peeing on a Jellyfish Sting Really Help It Heal? Here's What Experts Say Health'.

Photo by Health on August 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Should you pee on a jellyfish sting? The simple answer is no. "There is no scientific evidence whatsoever to support urinating on a jellyfish sting," Francis L. Counselman, MD, chair of emergency medicine at Eastern Virginia Medical School, tells Health. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Why do people believe this myth? The TV show Friends is partially to blame, according to Dr. Counselman. In the first episode of season four, "The One With the Jellyfish," Joey and Chandler convince Monica that urinating on a particularly painful sting on her foot could help make the pain go away. According to them, it works. But a 1990s sitcom isn't the best source of medical advice. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'What would happen if you do pee on a jellyfish sting? In reality, "studies have shown that pee doesn't do any harm or good, and it's disgusting," Isabel M. Algaze-Gonzalez, MD, an emergency medicine specialist, tells Health. Urea, a compound found in urine, could possibly help un-stick tentacles by dissolving the sticky material they use to latch on. Usually, though, it's not concentrated enough in your urine to have this effect. Worse yet, using your own fluids could end up causing more pain by disrupting stingers' delicate chemical balance and triggering them to fire. Health'.

Photo by Health on August 20, 2021. May be an image of ‎text that says '‎So how should you treat a jellyfish sting? First, make sure you're not dealing with a severe reaction (think, stomach pain, headache, and nausea) that would warrant a trip to the ER. Pain, itchiness, and a rash where you were stung are all normal signs of a mild, localized reaction. In these cases, you can usually self-treat a jellyfish sting: 5 Get out of the water and remove the stingers. ל Pour vinegar over the sting site. 5 Apply hot water. Relieve pain and swelling with OTC medications. Health‎'‎.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by Health on August 19, 2021 tagging @fallonlindsey. May be an image of 2 people, people standing and indoor.

node.text:
Fallon Melillo has gone viral on TikTok for sharing her story of being denied entry to a party bus because of her size—and she's using her experience to teach others about size acceptance.
.
@fallonlindsey tells Health that the posting for the party bus had a disclaimer that said, "Sorry, no big girls for this party! The doorman is very strict on appearance. If you have had problems getting into exclusive clubs before, then this is not for you! Please don't waste your time nor ours thinking that we can get you inside if you do not meet the qualifications."
.
"I was confused at first and then annoyed because what is a 'big girl?'" Melillo says. When Melillo and her friends showed up to board the party bus as planned, they were denied entry. "I was just very uncomfortable in that moment and wanted to leave.”
.
Melillo stresses that she is not the only one who has been through something like this. "Fat people experience discrimination for how they look all the time," she says. "Bigger people just want to live in their body in peace—go to events and have fun. But so many plus-size people will avoid events or more specifically nightlife for reasons like this."
.
Melillo urges other people to take her experience as a teaching lesson about fatphobia. "People don't think fatphobia exists, or they say they aren't fatphobic because they're not fearful of fat people," she says. "Even though that may be true, you are most likely fearful to look like a fat person or gain weight....Maybe you silently judge a bigger person eating out in a restaurant. Maybe you think to yourself 'wow she should not be wearing that bathing suit.' That is fatphobia."
.
Tap the link in bio for the full story 👆
